JOHANNESBURG - Former president Jacob Zuma and his lawyers might take the decision to prosecute him on review. His lawyer Michael Hulley says the reason for the decision is not clear from the "one-page and somewhat terse response" received from National Director of Public Prosecutions Shaun Abraham "advising that the representations made on behalf of Zuma were unsuccessful". #Breaking: Attorney for #JacobZuma Michael Hulley says Zuma is likely to take decision of NDPP #ShaunAbrahams on review. @eNCA pic.twitter.com/19MaDareIK WATCH: Zuma to face prosecution The NPA announced that the former president will face 16 charges relating to fraud, corruption and racketeering for his alleged involvement in the arms deal. eNCA